Anonymous Sat 21 Nov 2020 00:46:07 No.34228124 Report
Quoted By: >>34228772 >>34231311
>>34227603
I find it most annoying when it's used as a framing device for the character meant to put them on equal footing with the reader. As in, they would logically have some sort of specific knowledge, but now they have to re-learn it, paving the way for exposition and the like. For instance, the character wakes up in a village of people who rescued him, assists them in turn, fights off people who are hostile to them, and then discovers he was one of the enemy all along (bonus points if he was their leader) and has now learned a Very Important Lesson. Retrograde amnesia is a serious condition, and everyone would (or should) treat it seriously, characters and writer alike. Amnesia with a story function and cause is automatically better than crutch amnesia. For instance, in the Star Trek TNG episode Future Imperfect the main character wakes up to find himself much older, and is told that he contracted a mysterious virus in the intro that just woke up and erased his entire memory since then. But he's really important, and has to do a job no-one else can. Of course, it's all revealed as shenanigans when he starts picking at the borders of the illusion.

Just avoid crutch amnesia at all costs. If you plan to use this trope, ask yourself the question whether the story could function without it. Are you using it to hide information from the reader? Is it unrelated to any other plot points other than the results of the character having amnesia? Does part of the plot require characters not treating amnesia as the serious illness it is? All of these are hard no question.

Anonymous Sat 21 Nov 2020 01:42:02 No.34229261 Report
Quoted By:
>>34228772
ME2 isn't the best example for me, because it's the game that made me stop trusting Bioware, and AAA developers in general. However, what you have to ask yourself is what you want to achieve with this framing device. The function in ME2 is pretty clear: It's a sequel, and it's there to provide a fast-forward for the player. It being a video game is crucial, because the player directly controls the character. The character having more knowledge than the player doesn't mesh with that, and the medium isn't great at conveying such missing knowledge. Its strength is in interactivity. But it isn't the same for written fiction. Large leaps in time can be accommodated fairly comfortably.

If it's all just for exposition... well, I see no reason why it couldn't be added without resorting to a crutch to excuse speaking directly to the reader. Most stories do without And an exposition dump is still an exposition dump, and reads exactly the same, regardless of the reason for it being there.

Not to say you can never use this sort of stuff. I mean, you can do anything you want. If it's about a character re-adjusting to the world after shit changed on him, that's fine. It's just frivolous, pointless use that annoys me.
